ManSection.Description:
      This function returns true if f is a regular element of the 
      transformation semigroup S and false if it is not.


      A transformation f is regular in a transformation semigroup
      S if it lies inside a regular &D;-class; see  or .  Equivalently f is regular if the orbit
      of the image of f containing a transversal of the kernel of
      f; see  and .


gap> S:=Monoid(Transformation([2,2,4,4,5,6]),Transformation([5,3,4,4,6,6]));;
gap> f:=Generators(S)[1];;
gap> IsRegularTransformation(S, f);
true
gap> img:=ImageSetOfTransformation(f);
[ 2, 4, 5, 6 ]
gap> o:=Orb(S, img, OnSets);; Enumerate(o);
<closed orbit, 3 points>
gap> ForAny(o, x-> IsInjectiveTransOnList(f, x));
true
gap> IsRegularTransformation(S, Generators(S)[2]);
false
gap> IsRegularTransformation(FullTransformationSemigroup(6), Generators(S)[2]);
true

      This function returns an idempotent with  equal to ker and image set equal
      to img after first checking that  holds with argument ker, img.  


     IdempotentNC returns an idempotent with 

     equal to ker and image set equal to img without
     checking that  holds.

gap> f:=Transformation( [ 10, 2, 3, 10, 5, 10, 7, 2, 5, 6 ] );;
gap> ker:=CanonicalTransSameKernel(f);
[ 1, 2, 3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 2, 4, 6 ]
gap> img:=ImageSetOfTransformation(f);
[ 2, 3, 5, 6, 7, 10 ]
gap> Idempotent(ker, img);
Transformation( [ 6, 2, 3, 6, 5, 6, 7, 2, 5, 10 ] )

      If the partial permutation f is a permutation of
      the set of positive integers set, then AsPermutation
      returns this permutation;  see .


      If the optional argument set is not specified, then the image set
      of f is used by default for transformations and the range of
      f is used by default for partial permutations; see 
       and 
      .


gap> f:=Transformation( [ 5, 8, 3, 5, 8, 6, 2, 2, 7, 8 ] );;
gap> AsPermutation(f);
fail
gap> f:=Transformation( [ 8, 2, 10, 2, 4, 4, 7, 6, 9, 10 ] );;
gap> AsPermutation(f);
fail
gap> f:=Transformation( [ 1, 3, 6, 6, 2, 10, 2, 3, 10, 5 ] );;
gap> AsPermutation(f);
(2,3,6,10,5)
gap> f:=Transformation( [ 5, 2, 8, 4, 1, 8, 10, 3, 5, 7 ] );;
gap> AsPermutation(f);       
(1,5)(3,8)(7,10)
gap> AsPermutation(f, [1,5]);
(1,5)
gap> AsPermutation(f, [3,8,7,10]);
(3,8)(7,10)
gap> f:=PartialPerm([ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 11, 12, 16, 17, 18, 19 ],
> [ 3, 12, 14, 4, 11, 18, 17, 2, 9, 5, 15, 8, 20, 10, 19 ]);;
gap> AsPermutation(f);
fail
gap> AsPermutation(f, [4,5,11]);
(5,11)
gap> f:=RandomPartialPerm(20);;
gap> AsPermutation(f^-1*f);
()

NrElementsOfRank returns the number of elements of the
    semigroup S of partial permutations or transformations with rank
    n; see 
     and
    .


gap> S:=Semigroup( Transformation( [ 1, 3, 4, 1, 3 ] ), 
> Transformation( [ 2, 4, 1, 5, 5 ] ), 
> Transformation( [ 2, 5, 3, 5, 3 ] ), 
> Transformation( [ 4, 1, 2, 2, 1 ] ), 
>  Transformation( [ 5, 5, 1, 1, 3 ] ) );;
gap> NrElementsOfRank(S, 10);
0
gap> Size(S);
602
gap> List([1..5], x-> NrElementsOfRank(S, x));
[ 5, 260, 336, 1, 0 ]
gap> Sum(last);
602
gap> T:=FullTransformationSemigroup(5);;
gap> List([1..5], x-> NrElementsOfRank(T, x));
[ 5, 300, 1500, 1200, 120 ]
gap> Sum(last);
3125
gap> S:=SymmetricInverseSemigroup(5);;
gap> NrElementsOfRank(S, 4);
600
gap> Binomial(5,4)^2*Factorial(4);
600

    The argument ker should equal CanonicalTransSameKernel(g);
    for some transformation g with degree equal to the degree of the
    transformation f. 

    OnKernelsAntiAction returns CanonicalTransSameKernel(f*g).
    See also .


gap> f:=Transformation( [ 3, 6, 9, 2, 4, 2, 2, 2, 8, 2 ] );;
gap> g:=Transformation( [ 7, 1, 4, 3, 2, 7, 7, 6, 6, 5 ] );;
gap> ker:=CanonicalTransSameKernel(f);
[ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 4, 4, 4, 6, 4 ]
gap> OnKernelsAntiAction(ker, g);
[ 1, 2, 1, 3, 4, 1, 1, 1, 1, 5 ]
gap> CanonicalTransSameKernel(g*f);
[ 1, 2, 1, 3, 4, 1, 1, 1, 1, 5 ]
